  <!-- ═══ METHODOLOGY ═══ -->
  <h2>Methodology: Two-Stage DCF</h2>
  <p>We use a <strong>two-stage discounted cash flow (DCF)</strong> model to calculate the intrinsic value of Williams Companies. For energy infrastructure companies, debt loads are typically very high, and maintenance capex vs. growth capex is a key distinction.</p>

  <div class="method-step">
    <div class="step-num">1</div>
    <div class="step-content">
      <h4>Start with Base Cash Flow</h4>
      <p>WMB generated <strong>${fcfBase !== null ? fcfBase.toLocaleString() : 'N/A'} million</strong> in Free Cash Flow in the most recent period. As a pipeline operator with a "toll road" business model handling roughly one-third of US natural gas, cash flows are highly stable.</p>
    </div>
  </div>

  <div class="method-step">
    <div class="step-num">2</div>
    <div class="step-content">
      <h4>Project FCF growth for 5 years (Phase 1)</h4>
      <p>We grow FCF at <strong>{(growthRatePhase1 * 100).toFixed(1)}% per year</strong> for 5 years. This reflects WMB's strong position in natural gas infrastructure, fee-based contracts with inflation escalators, and execution on growth projects.</p>
    </div>
  </div>

  <div class="method-step">
    <div class="step-num">3</div>
    <div class="step-content">
      <h4>Calculate terminal value (Phase 2)</h4>
      <p>After Year 5, we assume FCF grows at <strong>{(growthRateTerminal * 100).toFixed(1)}% forever</strong>. This is slightly below long-term GDP growth, acknowledging the eventual, long-term energy transition away from fossil fuels, while recognizing natural gas as a necessary bridge fuel for decades.</p>
    </div>
  </div>

  <div class="method-step">
    <div class="step-num">4</div>
    <div class="step-content">
      <h4>Discount everything to present value</h4>
      <p>All future cash flows are discounted at <strong>{(discountRate * 100).toFixed(1)}%</strong>. This required rate of return is appropriate for a regulated/toll-road pipeline utility, balancing the 10Y Treasury (4.18%) and WMB's stable, investment-grade profile.</p>
    </div>
  </div>

  <div class="method-step">
    <div class="step-num">5</div>
    <div class="step-content">
      <h4>Add net cash, divide by shares</h4>
      <p>Enterprise Value + Net Cash (${netCash !== null ? netCash.toLocaleString() : 'N/A'}M) = Equity Value. Pipeline companies run with high debt, so Net Cash is heavily negative. We divide by shares outstanding ({sharesOutstanding !== null ? sharesOutstanding.toLocaleString() : 'N/A'}M) for the per-share intrinsic value.</p>
    </div>
  </div>

  <!-- ═══ THE THREE ASSUMPTIONS ═══ -->
