  <!-- ═══ WHAT THE MODEL DOESN'T CAPTURE ═══ -->
  <h2>Risks & What This Model Misses</h2>
  <ul>
    <li><strong>Interest Rate Risk:</strong> As a high-yield infrastructure stock, WMB trades inversely to interest rates. If the 10Y Treasury spikes above 5%, the required discount rate will rise, compressing the intrinsic value.</li>
    <li><strong>Regulatory Blocking:</strong> Expanding pipelines faces severe regulatory and environmental hurdles. If WMB cannot execute its growth capex backlog due to permitting failures, the 5% growth rate is at risk.</li>
    <li><strong>Debt Load:</strong> With over ${totalDebt !== null ? (totalDebt/1000).toFixed(1) : 'N/A'}B in debt, a significant portion of operating cash flow goes to interest expenses. A credit downgrade would increase capital costs.</li>
    <li><strong>AI Power Demand:</strong> This model may be too conservative if AI data centers drive a massive, unforecasted spike in US natural gas consumption, requiring heavily expanded pipeline throughput.</li>
  </ul>

  <!-- ═══ FAQ ═══ -->
  <h2>Frequently Asked Questions</h2>
  <div class="faq">
    <details>
      <summary>Why use standard Free Cash Flow for a pipeline company?</summary>
      <div class="faq-answer">Midstream companies often emphasize Distributable Cash Flow (DCF) because heavy growth capex depresses standard FCF. However, true intrinsic value must account for the cash spent to achieve growth. Since WMB generates positive standard FCF even after capex, we use it as the purest measure of cash generation available to equity holders.</div>
    </details>
    <details>
      <summary>How does WMB's debt impact the valuation?</summary>
      <div class="faq-answer">Significantly. The model calculates the Enterprise Value first (value of the entire firm operations), and then strictly subtracts all Total Debt to arrive at Equity Value. The massive debt pile acts as an anchor on the per-share value, which is standard for capital-intensive infrastructure.</div>
    </details>
    <details>
      <summary>Is this a buy recommendation?</summary>
      <div class="faq-answer">No. This is an analytical framework for estimating intrinsic value. Whether to buy depends on your personal risk tolerance, portfolio allocation, time horizon, tax situation, and conviction in the assumptions.</div>
    </details>
  </div>

